    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_001",
      "passage": "A physiology lab studies stair climbing in volunteers wearing portable metabolic monitors. A participant with mass 70 kg climbs a vertical height of 12 m in 20 s. The center of mass is modeled as rising vertically, and mechanical work against gravity is estimated with W = mgh using g \u2248 10 m/s\u00b2. The monitor also estimates chemical energy expenditure, which is greater than mechanical work because skeletal muscle is not perfectly efficient.\n\nCondition | Vertical height | Time | Mechanical work | Average mechanical power\nTrial 1 | 12 m | 20 s | ? | ?\nTrial 2 | 12 m | 10 s | same work | higher power\n\nThe investigator notes that work depends on force and displacement in the direction of force, whereas power depends on rate of energy transfer. A second analysis compares concentric muscle contraction during upward stepping with isometric contraction while holding position.",
      "stem": "What is the approximate mechanical work done against gravity in Trial 1?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "1.2 \u00d7 10\u00b2 J"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "8.4 \u00d7 10\u00b3 J"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "1.4 \u00d7 10\u2074 J"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "5.9 \u00d7 10\u2074 J"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "This value is too small because it effectively omits either body mass or most of the height term. The gravitational work must include mass, g, and vertical displacement.",
        "B": "Correct. Work against gravity is W = mgh = (70 kg)(10 m/s\u00b2)(12 m) = 8.4 \u00d7 10\u00b3 J. The time required does not affect the work for the same vertical displacement; it affects power.",
        "C": "This is too large for the given height and mass and likely comes from using an incorrect height or double-counting a factor. The straightforward product is 8.4 kJ.",
        "D": "This value is far too large and would correspond to a much greater vertical height or mass. Stair-climbing work here is kilojoules, not tens of kilojoules for 12 m."
      },
      "topic": "Mechanical Work",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageImage": "data:image/png;base64,"
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_002",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "What is the average mechanical power in Trial 1?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "420 W"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "84 W"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "840 W"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "8400 W"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. Power is work divided by time: P = 8.4 \u00d7 10\u00b3 J / 20 s = 420 W. Trial 2 has the same work but less time, so power increases.",
        "B": "84 W divides by about 100 s rather than 20 s. It underestimates the rate at which mechanical energy is transferred during the climb.",
        "C": "840 W would be correct if the same work were done in 10 s, as in Trial 2. It is not the Trial 1 power because Trial 1 takes 20 s.",
        "D": "8400 W confuses work in joules with power in watts. The numerical work value must still be divided by time to obtain watts."
      },
      "topic": "Power",
