    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_005",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "During an isometric hold at fixed height, external mechanical work on the center of mass is approximately zero because:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "force may be present but displacement of the center of mass is zero."
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "ATP use must also be zero."
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "gravity no longer acts on the body."
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "muscles cannot generate tension without shortening."
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. Mechanical work is the component of force times displacement. During a static hold, muscles generate force, but if the center of mass does not move, external work on it is approximately zero even though ATP is consumed internally.",
        "B": "Isometric contraction can consume ATP for cross-bridge cycling and ion handling. Zero external work does not imply zero metabolic cost.",
        "C": "Gravity still acts during the hold and must be balanced by muscle and skeletal forces. The absence of center-of-mass displacement is what makes external work approximately zero.",
        "D": "Muscles can generate tension isometrically without macroscopic shortening. That is the entire point of an isometric contraction."
      },
      "topic": "Isometric Work",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "cp_energy2_001",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_006",
      "passage": "A rehabilitation engineer evaluates a prosthetic knee that stores elastic energy during early stance and releases some of it during push-off. Force-platform data estimate changes in kinetic energy and potential energy during walking. On level ground, the device reduces metabolic cost when it returns stored elastic energy at the correct phase of gait. On a ramp, the system must add net positive work during ascent and absorb net negative work during descent.\n\nWalking condition | Net mechanical work by prosthesis | Metabolic effect\nLevel ground, timed release | near zero over cycle | lower cost\nRamp ascent | positive | assists lifting\nRamp descent | negative | controlled braking\n\nThe team warns that energy conservation does not mean energy is always useful: energy can be dissipated as heat if released at the wrong time or absorbed by damping elements.",
      "stem": "Why can elastic energy return lower metabolic cost during level walking?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Energy stored elastically is destroyed before it can be used."
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Timed release can substitute for some active muscle work during push-off."
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Elastic storage requires ATP hydrolysis inside the prosthesis."
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Returning energy at any time is equally useful."
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Stored elastic energy is not necessarily destroyed; it can be returned if damping and timing allow. The passage says the device lowers cost when release is properly timed.",
        "B": "Correct. If elastic energy is released during the phase when positive work is needed, it can reduce the active muscle or motor work required. The timing matters because mechanical energy must be delivered when it contributes to gait.",
        "C": "A passive elastic element can store and return mechanical energy without ATP. ATP is relevant to biological muscle, not necessarily to the prosthetic spring mechanism.",
        "D": "The passage explicitly warns that mistimed energy can be dissipated as heat or fail to assist motion. Usefulness depends on phase, not only energy amount."
      },
      "topic": "Elastic Energy Return",
      "difficulty": "Medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_007",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "On ramp ascent, why must the prosthesis or user add net positive work?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Negative work raises the center of mass."
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Kinetic energy must always be zero on ramps."
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "The body-prosthesis system gains gravitational potential energy."
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Energy conservation forbids climbing."
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Negative work removes mechanical energy or controls motion. It cannot by itself raise the center of mass against gravity.",
        "B": "Walking on a ramp can involve kinetic energy fluctuations, but the need for positive work comes from increased height, not zero kinetic energy.",
        "C": "Correct. Ascending a ramp raises the center of mass, increasing gravitational potential energy. That requires net positive work from the user, prosthesis, or both.",
        "D": "Energy conservation does not forbid climbing; it requires that the increase in potential energy come from chemical or device-supplied energy."
      },
      "topic": "Potential Energy in Gait",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "passageRef": "cp_energy2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
