      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Which condition best represents controlled energy absorption?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Standing still with no damping"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Ramp ascent with positive work"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Level walking with perfectly timed return"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Ramp descent with negative prosthesis work"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "D",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Standing still may involve forces but does not describe controlled absorption of gait energy. The passage identifies ramp descent as the negative-work case.",
        "B": "Ramp ascent requires adding energy, not absorbing it. Positive work assists lifting the body upward.",
        "C": "Timed return on level ground recycles energy rather than primarily absorbing net energy over the cycle. It can reduce cost, but it is not the clearest negative-work condition.",
        "D": "Correct. During descent, the system must remove mechanical energy to control lowering of the body. Negative prosthesis work corresponds to absorbing energy, often through damping or controlled braking."
