    {
      "id": "cp_energy2_010",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Which statement best distinguishes work from energy in the prosthesis example?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Work is energy transfer by force through displacement; stored energy is capacity that may or may not be usefully transferred."
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Work and energy have unrelated units."
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Stored energy always equals useful work delivered to the body."
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Only chemical systems can store energy."
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. Work is a mode of energy transfer, specifically force acting through displacement. Elastic energy stored in the prosthesis is potential capacity, but it becomes useful work only if released in the right mechanical context.",
        "B": "Work and energy share units of joules. They are conceptually distinct but dimensionally related.",
        "C": "Stored energy can be lost to damping or released at an unhelpful time. The passage explicitly warns against equating stored energy with useful work.",
        "D": "Mechanical systems can store energy elastically or gravitationally. Chemical storage is only one form of energy storage."
      },
      "topic": "Work-Energy Distinction",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
